,Recommended,643810,34981250,Posted: 15 September,all,RandomDude93,"TL;DR: Visually stunning and a load of fun to fly. Intuitive once you have a grasp of the controls. If you have a problem with diamonds in the rough, don't buy this game just yet. Otherwise, it's definitely worth your $$, especially if you're into flying and like infinite worlds.More detail:Epic: The terrain generation works like a treat. Smooth and fast, even when you're rocketing along at max speed (which feels like podracing XD ). With the right settings, you get a lot of fun caves and passages to fly through, and with a few minutes of practice, you can even navigate them decently.Great: Good variety of 'bird' models and full shift/partial shift stages. Personally had some fun with the flying bear type.Needs work: -XBox 360 Controller input was super, super twitchy.-Mouse input lags pretty hard.-Most of the birds fly really fast and barely glide, which makes it difficult to be precise in tight spots. I'd prefer if flight were less hectic and visibility a little better as a trade off. It's supposed to be meditative, after all.-Flapping mechanics are primitive at the moment, and landing is weird.-Also, the unpredictable shift mechanic is irritating sometimes. Would be better if you only changed shape on command and when targeting a viable creature/plant/whatever.Summary: It's very much an early access game, but one that (glitches, bugs and crashes aside for now) could develop from an amazing concept to something truly spectacular. I will definitely keep coming back to this, because it's great if you just want to unplug for a bit and fly."
